16 2021-01-24 injection site pain Client came to be vaccinated accompanied by her father on Saturday January 23, 2021. The greeting ta... Read more
Close
Client came to be vaccinated accompanied by her father on Saturday January 23, 2021. The greeting table in the front was very busy and a lot going on. The client had registered online and had her paper to prove it when she was escorted to he next tables to be registered. There was nothing adverse about her registration form. Date of birth was listed, however, it was not caught that she was less than 18 to receive Moderna. We advertise that it is the Moderna vaccine that we have. Father never said anything and stood off to the side waiting for her to be observed for 15 minutes. On Monday, January 25, I spoke with client who answered phone, to explain what happened and to see if she was OK. States her arm at injection site hurt a little, but nothing else. I said I would call each day to make sure she was OK. Later in the day, she left a message to call her. I called and she wanted to know what vaccine she would get as her second dose. I said it would not be Moderna and that I could find some information and call her back. Then she states she has a lawyer and to whom should she address it to. I said the Health Officer at the city.
16 2021-02-03 vaccination site pain 16 year old inadvertently received the vaccine; sore arm; supposed to receive the Pfizer vaccine but... Read more
Close
16 year old inadvertently received the vaccine; sore arm; supposed to receive the Pfizer vaccine but received the Moderna covid-19 vaccine by mistake; A spontaneous report was received from a healthcare professional (HCP) concerning a 16-year-old, female consumer who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) was less than 18 years old and had a sore arm. The patient's medical history was not provided. No relevant concomitant medications were reported. On 06 Jan 2021 prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number : 025J20A) intramuscularly in the left deltoid for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 06 Jan 2021, a 16-year-old patient was inadvertently vaccinated. The patient was supposed to receive Pfizer vaccine but received Moderna COVID- 19 vaccine by mistake. The patient experienced a sore arm but no other known symptoms. No treatment was received for the sore arm. Action taken with the second dose of mRNA-1273 in response to the event was not reported. The event, vaccine given to a patient less than 18-years-old, and wrong drug administered was considered resolved. The outcome for the patient's sore arm was not reported.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 16-year-old female patient who received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot unknown), reporting Product administered to patient of inappropriate age and Wrong product administered with an associated non-serious expected event of Injection site pain. No treatment received for the event. Based on temporal association between the use of the product and the onset of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

Had very mild pain in left arm; 16 year old daughter injected with Moderna vaccine; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer, concerning a 16-year-old female patient, who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine, where 16-year-old daughter injected with Moderna vaccine had very mild pain in left arm. The patient's medical history reported included severe asthma. Concomitant product use was not provided by the reporter. On 28 JAN 2021, prior to the onset of event, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (lot number unknown) intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 28 JAN 2021, a 16-year-old patient was injected with vaccine and had no reactions of fever or any other adverse events. Later, on an unspecified date in 2021, she also experienced very mild pain in her left arm where she was vaccinated. The patient was under asthma medications twice a day for her asthma. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events were not reported. The outcome of the event, 16-year-old daughter injected with Moderna vaccine was considered resolved on 28 JAN 2021. The outcome of the event had very mild pain in left arm was considered unknown at the time of this report.; Reporter's Comments: The events developed on same day after first dose of mRNA-1372. Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event of vaccination site pain, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

Received the COVID vaccine at age 16; Injecstion site pain; A spontaneous report was received from a physician regarding his daughter who is a 17-year-old female, unknown race and ethnicity, who was administered Moderna Covid-19 vaccine and experienced pain at injection site. The patient's medical history was not provided. No concomitant medications were reported. No information on allergies. On 22-Jan-2021, prior to the onset of events, patient received her first of two planned doses of Moderna Covid-19 vaccine intramuscularly for the prophylaxis of Covid-19 infection. (Lot#011J20A). The physician who is patient's father would like to give her the second dose. Also, he wanted to consider her for pediatric trials. Action taken with vaccine is physician showed willingness to give his daughter a second dose. The outcome of the events, inappropriate age at vaccination and pain at injection site is unknown at the time of report.; Reporter's Comments: This report refers to a case of product administered to patient of inappropriate age (17 year old) for mRNA-1273 (Lot # 011J20A) with pain at injection site reported. Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

Injection site pain and tenderness; 16 year old patient administered the vaccine; A spontaneous report was received from a health care provider regarding a 16-year-old female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) inappropriately at the age of 16 and experienced injection site pain and tenderness/vaccination site pain. The patient's medical history was not included. Products known to have been used by the patient were Vitamin D3 and ethinylestradiol, ferrous fumarate, norethisterone. On 12 Feb 2021, prior to the onset of the events, the patient inappropriately received the first of two doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 031M20A) intramuscularly in the right deltoid for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 13 Feb 2021, the day after the vaccine was given the patient experienced injection site pain and tenderness. Treatment information was not provided. Action taken with mRNA-1273 was not reported. The outcome of the events, vaccine being given inappropriately to a 16-year-old, was considered resolved on 12 Feb 2021. The event, vaccine site pain and tenderness, was unknown.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 16-year-old female patient who received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot 031M20A), reporting Product administered to patient of inappropriate age with associated adverse event of vaccination site pain. Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the onset date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

16 2021-04-17 vaccination site pain As patient was in the upstairs lobby the check-in nurse caught that the patient received Moderna as ... Read more
Close
As patient was in the upstairs lobby the check-in nurse caught that the patient received Moderna as their first dose on 03/21/2021. Patient is 16 years old and was returning today for their second dose. Check-in nurse alerted myself Nurse Co-Lead. Nurse Co-Lead elevated the situation to Clinical Operations Coordinator, whom verified and approved for patient to receive the second dose of Moderna according to CDC interim considerations. Nurse Co-Lead verified that patient received the first dose of Moderna at the health center and on the patient's immunization record. First 0.5 ML IM dose of Moderna lot #046A21A administered on 03/21/2021. Second 0.5 ML IM dose of Moderna lot #042B21A administered on 04/18/2021. Patient denied adverse reaction to both doses of Moderna, only slight soreness at vaccination site for first dose on 03/21/2021. Nurse Co-Lead then spoke to all Moderna vaccinators and ancillary staff assigned for 04/18/2021, I reiterated the correct age groups for both Moderna and Pfizer. Our vaccination sites have today's date for allowing to vaccinate to which age group and for which vaccine on the walls of each nursing station within the vaccinator's view. In addition, our reception desk inside the building and now outside check in table have these daily reminders visibly in front of them. Nurse Co-Lead spoke to the nurse specifically that administered the first dose of Moderna on 03/21/2021 and re-educated the medication rights and agreed to the methods in preventing this error in the future. Nurse Co-Lead spoke to Lead Ancillary to re-educate and reiterate her ancillary staff each day as well. Nurse Lead produced a new nurse station safety checklist that includes medication rights, correct age group for each vaccine, and verbal consent from patient, and the 3 contraindication questions for the vaccinator/nurse to hold the vaccine. Nurse Co-Lead spoke to lead registration table ancillary lead as well as the site manager that oversees the ancillary staff outside the building as initial check in staff. Nurse Co-Lead and Nurse Lead agreed to have end of day huddle to re-iterate today's captured vaccination error and methods to prevent in the future. Patient along with her legal Guardian verbally consented and agreed to complete Moderna series.

Close
Rash and itchiness started at around 10 PM on 1/7/2021. Rash described as "traveling across chest" and similar to what happens when she takes prednisone. Stated she has not taken prednisone for over a year. Client stated that rash did not appear anywhere else on her body. Itchiness was experienced on chest and arms only. Client also stated symptoms of fatigue, muscle weakness, and "super sore arm" that lasted from day of vaccination until 1/10/2021. Client also reported a headache that lasted 2 day after vaccination. She contacted her provider on 1/7/2021 and, per provider's instruction, took 1 tablet of Benadryl. Client was unsure of dosage of Benadryl. On the morning of 1/8/2021 she took a second tablet of Benadryl and reported that her rash resolved after the second dose of Benadryl. Her itchiness resolved the morning of 1/9/2021. Stated that her Doctor did not specify a diagnosis but did state to hold off on the second dose of this vaccine.

18 2021-01-13 itchy skin Patient was screened and identified allergy to PCN. Covid Vaccine administered without incident. Nu... Read more

Patient was screened and identified allergy to PCN. Covid Vaccine administered without incident. Nurse did insist client stay in area for 30 minutes due to history of PCN allergy. After about 10 minutes, client returned with complaint of itching, flushing in face and hyperventilating. LPH assisted and laid patient down and elevated her legs. Pulse was 200 and breathing difficulties increased. EPI 0.5 given IM in thigh by nurse. Patient felt significantly better after one dose of EPI and breathing was almost back to normal. Patient transported by EMS.

18 2021-01-14 hives I had no pain or discomfort immediately after the shot, during the 15 minute observation period, or ... Read more
Close
I had no pain or discomfort immediately after the shot, during the 15 minute observation period, or an hour after. About 2 hours later (at 2:00 pm), I developed some hives around my neck, and the part of my arm near the injection site started to become more and more sore. I applied Benadryl to the hives and they went away. However, my left arm hurt to touch or move, much worse than any vaccine I've had before (flu, HPV). That night, I had trouble sleeping because the discomfort because of the sore left arm. I also could not sleep because of chest tightness and pressure, which worsened when lying down, but that pressure did not progress to the point of wheezing (I have asthma). Sleeping on my back was the only option because sleeping on either side was painful, which worsened the chest pressure. When I woke up, my fingers felt stiff and I had joint pain in both hands, more so in my left hand. Throughout this, I did not see any redness on my arm. This day it was agonizing to move my left arm. I could pick things up, but raising it above my the height of my waist or twisting it behind my back to get on my backpack was near impossible and was avoided. The chest pressure went away. The second night, I still had trouble sleeping, but the pain was much better, although I still could not sleep on my side. When I woke up, I had no more joint pain. That day, although the left arm was still sore, I could move it pretty well. If I made too strong of a movement, it felt like the injection site would tense up, the pain would slowly ramp up, and then diminish. That afternoon, at 4:30, I was able to play tennis with minimal soreness, and that night, I was able to sleep on my side. The following day, I had a cough, but that might have been because I didn't dress for the weather, and experiences close to zero soreness.

18 2021-02-03 injection site pain For my first dose, I had quite mild symptoms. I woke up with a migraine the next morning and some so... Read more
Close
For my first dose, I had quite mild symptoms. I woke up with a migraine the next morning and some soreness at the injection site. Both of these lasted a couple of days and were able to be treated with over-the-counter pain medicine. My second dose, however, provided much worse flu-like symptoms. About 12 hours after I received the injection, I was woken with a migraine much worse than the first, nausea, chills, joint pain, sore throat, and fatigue. While the chills and nausea subsided, the other symptoms persisted until the next day. As of today (2/4/21), all symptoms are gone except for soreness at the injection site.

Close
1/24/21 morning, 10 days after getting 1st dose of vaccination, broke out in hives in several places on both feet. The next day more hives appeared on knees and the ones on feet got worse. The day after that hives also appeared on hips and elbows. On 1/27 went to Doctor's office and received steroid shot to stop the allergic reaction. Took 5-7 days for all the hives to disappear. Based on the allergic reaction to the first dose, doctor recommended not taking the second dose as reaction could be more severe and/or have an asthma attack.

Close
I got my shot, sat down, and was reading through the information that the clinic provided me. A few minutes after, I noticed my right arm was getting warm, but I thought I was being paranoid (placebo effect). I began to feel nauseated. About another 5 minutes after feeling warm and nauseous, my ears began to ring and my vision went white. I was cold but sweating. I have passed out a handful of times before for various reasons, so I knew what was happening. I tried to signal to a volunteer from my seat that I needed help, but I ended up laying on the ground by my chair before someone came over. Once I laid down, the attention of the volunteers and nurses was on me. Three came over to assist me. They held my legs up, kept a hand on my wrist for a pulse, and fetched water. I talked myself through the dizziness and ringing in my ears. They put a cold rag on my forehead and had smelling salts on hand. Once I began to feel better, they helped me slowly sit up, and eventually helped me stand up and get into a chair. They kept a close eye on me for the next 30 minutes to make sure I didn?t have any other reactions.

Red round rump below the deltoid muscle; Red round rump below the deltoid muscle; Injection was wrongly administered at the wrong muscle site; A spontaneous report was received from a nurse, concerning a 19-year-old female patient, who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and developed red round lump below the deltoid muscle/ vaccination site mass and vaccination site erythema, injection was wrongly administered at the wrong muscle site/ incorrect route of product administration. The patient's medical history was not reported. No relevant concomitant medications were reported. On 06 Jan 2021, prior to onset of event, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 025L20A) on right arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On an unknown date, after vaccination, the patient developed red round lump below the deltoid muscle and the patient's mother believed that the injection was wrongly administered at the wrong muscle site. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the event was unknown. The outcome of the event red round lump below the deltoid muscle was unknown. The outcome of event injection was wrongly administered at the wrong muscle site was considered resolved on 06 Jan 2021.; Reporter's Comments: This report refers to a case of Product administration error for mRNA-1273, lot # 025L20A with associated AEs. Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

Within 5 minutes after receiving vaccine, patient indicated that it felt like her whole body was on fire and she felt faint. She was already seated for observation following the dose. Lupus; Obstruction breathing; Lips were swollen; Hives on face/ huge welts all over body; Fever; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer concerning a 20-year-old, adult female patient, who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced lupus/systemic lupus erythematosus, fever/pyrexia, hives on face/huge welts all over body/urticaria, lips were swollen/lip swelling and obstruction breathing/obstructive airways disorder. The patient's medical history was not provided. Concomitant product use was not provided by the reporter. On an unspecified date in Jan 2021, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received the first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number: Unknown) for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On an unspecified date in Feb 2021, Patient received the second of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number: Unknown) for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On an unspecified date in Feb 2021, within 24 hours after receiving the second dose, patient experienced fever, hives on face/huge welts all over body, lips were swollen and obstruction breathing. The patient went to the ER and was given unspecified steriods and Diphenhydramine and the patient went to the ER (emergency room) on 19 Mar 2021 because she had another reaction and the doctor confirmed her that the vaccine triggered lupus. The event lupus was considered as medically significant. The patient received both scheduled doses of mRNA-1273 prior to the events; therefore, action taken with the drug in response to the events was not applicable. The outcome of the events, lupus, fever, hives on face/huge welts all over body, lips were swollen and obstruction breathing was unknown at the time of this report.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

21 2021-02-04 injection site inflammation, injection site redness, injection site warmth, injection site swelling, injection site pruritus, injection site pain About 3-4 hours after the injection was given, my left arm began to hurt at the sight of the injecti... Read more
Close
About 3-4 hours after the injection was given, my left arm began to hurt at the sight of the injection. It was sore red and beginning to swell. After a couple more hours it was difficult to even move my arm; it felt as if my tricep was almost entirely immobilized. These symptoms persisted for about three days, with increasingly less intensity, and after the fourth day, I had no adverse symptoms. Exactly six days after receiving the vaccine, the area where the injection was given (tricep) began to feel itchy. When I tried to scratch it, the itch was not relieved but only worsened and began to swell and turn red. By the following day (7 days after injection), the site of injection and area surrounding the site of injection (about 6 inches along my upper and 3-4 inches in width) had swelled up more and was significantly more inflamed than my opposite arm which hadn't changed at all. It had a similar swelling, itch, and pain to the sensation one experiences after getting bitten by a mosquito, but in this case a very very large mosquito bite. By the evening of the seventh day, I began feeling very fatigued both mentally and physically and felt very subtle body aches that usually signal the early signs of a fever (at least for me). Upon feeling feverish symptoms I made a drink of turmeric and ginger root powder with honey and laid down for about an hour in an attempt to rest. After an hour, the body aches and fatigue lessened in intensity but my arm was still swelling and now feeling hot in temperature. The itching was unbearable. I went to go take a warm shower later that night and started to feel a mixture of pressure and pain traveling up my arm and into my chest. I began feeling my lymph nodes on the left side of my breast to find that a lymph node in my armpit and another one on the side of my breast had enlarged to about two inches in diameter. They were painful to the touch and noticeably sore when left untouched. These symptoms persisted with no change for about 2 days. After two days, the swelling and itching in my arm went away but my lymph nodes were still inflamed. They did not reduce in size or in pain until about 7 days after the first signs of these symptoms. After a week all symptoms went away.

Fainting; Injection site soreness in arm; nauseous; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer concerning a 21-year-old, female patient, who received Moderna's COVID-19 Vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced, fainting (syncope), injection site soreness in arm (vaccination site pain), and nausea (nausea). The patient's medical history included vasovagal condition that cause heart rate and blood pressure to drop due to stress on body and dehydration resulting in fainting. Concomitant product use was not provided by the reporter. On 09 Feb 2021, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 013M20A) intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 09 Feb 2021, the patient was fine until about 11 pm after which she experienced arm soreness on the injection site and felt nauseous. On 10 Feb 2021, at 5 am in the morning, the patient fainted. The patient assumed that shot might have added stress to her body which most likely caused her to faint. No treatment information was provided. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was unknown. There was no change planned to the dosing schedule of mRNA-1273 in response to the event as patient would be receiving second dose on 09 Mar 2021. The outcome of events, fainted (syncope), injection site soreness in arm (vaccination site pain), and nauseous (nausea), were considered as unknown.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the onset date of the reported events of syncope, vaccination site pain, and nausea, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. Patient's prior medical history of vasovagal reactions is considered a contributing factor to syncope.

21 2021-04-27 injection site bleeding At 10:40, the patient went in for her first Moderna vax. She was slightly nervous since she's not a... Read more
Close
At 10:40, the patient went in for her first Moderna vax. She was slightly nervous since she's not a fan of needles. When she got it a vessel must have been nicked, because she experienced a bit of blood streaming down her arm which surprised us. The nurse wasn't concerned and stopped it quickly and cleaned up her arm. Got her a new bandaid and she was sent to the chairs in the waiting area to wait her 15 minutes following the vax. I had to pick up my regular prescription so I got in line while she was sitting there surfing on her phone. As I got to the front of the line, the patient called me and said she was feeling lightheaded. I immediately left the line, and was there (I was maybe 15 feet away) and was asking how she felt. She said she felt sweaty and like she might pass out. Right then, her eyes rolled a bit and closed and she went limp. I was able to hold on to her and a customer that was behind me in line and I were able to alert the nurse that gave the vax and the pharmacist. Both immediately came to our aid. We got the patient on the floor and on her side. The nurse wanted us to have an epi pen in case, but we all didn't think it was an allergic reaction. We checked her blood pressure and it was low. Another employee was already calling an ambulance and another was getting her some juice. She was beginning to regain consciousness. She was only out for about 2 to 3 minutes at the most. Her blood pressure was low, but started to come back to normal pretty quickly. We had her lay there a few minutes and then sit up. Eventually we moved her to the chair a few minutes later. Within another few minutes the emts arrived. She had already had answered questions for us like her name, birthday, where she was, etc. The emts repeated those same questions, asked us what happened and rechecked her vitals. All were back to normal. They gave her the option of be transported to the ER, but given that she was feeling back to normal she declined and everybody felt good about that decision.

22 2021-02-16 injection site pruritus, injection site numbness, injection site pain Aggravated very quickly; Everything went blank; She can't talk and when she tries to talk she feels ... Read more
Close
Aggravated very quickly; Everything went blank; She can't talk and when she tries to talk she feels like she has the hiccups where she can barely get the words to talk; when she has a hiccup her whole chest hurts; Hiccup; Numbness; Her whole right side would jerk uncontrollably; Weak; fever; itching; sore arm / burning; chills; A spontaneous report (United States) was received from a consumer who was also a 22-year-old female patient, who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine who experienced sore arm/ burning (injection site pain), fever (pyrexia), chills, itching (injection site pruritus), numbness (injection site numbness), weak (asthenia), whole right side would jerk uncontrollably (myoclonus), everything went blank (loss of consciousness), couldn't talk and when she tried to talk she felt like she had the hiccups (aphasia), her whole chest hurt (chest discomfort), and quickly became aggravated (anger). The patient's medical history was not provided. Concomitant product use was not provided by the reporter. On 06 Jan 2021, the patient received her first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 intramuscularly in her right deltoid for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 06 Jan 2021, the patient experienced a sore arm, fever, chills, itching and burning. On 07 Jan 2021, on the site where the patient received the injection, she felt numbness and weak. Her whole right-side body would jerk uncontrollably. The patient went to two emergency rooms where they stated they did not know what was wrong and gave her a steroid injection that temporarily helped calm her down. On 08 Jan 2021, the patient stared at the door and everything went blank. She could not talk and when she tried to talk, she felt like she had the hiccups. She experienced her whole chest hurting when she had a hiccup. On 25 Jan 2021 and 26 Jan 2021, the patient saw two neurologists, who did testing. The patient's jerking was random, there were no triggers for it, and she did not know how to control or stop it. These adverse reactions made the patient become aggravated very quickly, which was not like her. On an unknown date, the patient stated it was the first day in the past month she had been able to talk all day. Treatment for the events included a steroid shot. Action taken with the second dose of mRNA-1273 in response to the event was not reported. The outcome for the events, sore arm/ burning, fever, chills, itching, numbness, weak, whole right side would jerk uncontrollably, everything went blank, couldn't talk and when she tried to talk she felt like she had the hiccups and her whole chest hurt, and quickly became aggravated, was not reported.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information which indicates a strong temporal association between the use of the product and the onset of the reported events a causal relationship cannot be excluded. Chills, fever, injection site pruritus and injection site pain are consistent with the known safety profile of mRNA-1273.

I ate a granola bar right after the Tylenol and started to feel a little better. Then I got really hungry, so I ate a muffin and drank an energy+ juice drink that had 80mg caffeine derived from green and black tea. I started to feel a lot better after that, though I was still weak and experiencing aching in my legs and hips. I took another nap from 7 p.m. to 9 p.m. and then ate once more before going to sleep for the night around 1:30 a.m. I have woken up today (5/5) with a slight headache but no other symptoms save the injection site soreness that has also persisted since a few hours after the shot. Close
I received my second dose of the Moderna COVID vaccine at approx. 10:40 AM on Friday, January 29 at clinic. By 12:00 PM, I noticed that I developed facial swelling, which was most significant around my eyes, and I felt lethargic. Between 12:00 PM and 2:00 PM, I developed hives on my neck, chest, stomach, and arms, which prompted me to take 1/2 of a dose of 25mg Benadryl. Nonetheless, the symptoms persisted and I began to experience dizziness and tightness in my throat around 4-5 PM, which was when I was advised by a nurse to go to the emergency room for treatment. I arrived at Hospital's Emergency Department around 6:00 PM and I was treated for "Possible Allergic Reaction Major." I received diphenhydrAMINE (BENADRYL) injection 50 mg, famotidine (PF) (PEPCID) injection 20 mg, methylPREDNISolone sodium succinate (PF) (SOLU-MEDROL) injection 125 mg, sodium chloride 0.9 % iv bolus, and acetaminophen (TYLENOL) tablet 650 mg. I was discharged after 10:00 PM and sent home with a prescription for predniSONE 20 mg and famotidine 20 mg. My facial swelling and hives have gone down but neither have completely resolved since being discharged. I am also experiencing full body aches and fatigue at this time (3 PM on Saturday, January 30).

Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA I received the vaccine on 3/13 at 3:45pm and began experiencing symptoms on the day at 5:30pm including dizziness, nausea, fatigue and wiped-out exhaustion, drunk-like dazed and confused, body heaviness, and developed soreness in the muscle of the right arm where the injection had been administered. The symptoms progressed at 6:30pm to include general muscle soreness, muscle twitching on the right side of the body especially on the right upper thigh, increased appetite, malaise, headache, and chills in addition to the aforementioned symptoms. At 7:30pm the nausea and increased appetite improved with food and fluid intake but sleepiness, yawning, confusion, chills, and fatigue worsened at 8:30pm. Temperature at 9:30pm was 95.7 degrees Fahrenheit and a pale, green-like, clammy appearance was visible on the general skin. At 10:30pm the sleepiness reversed to restlessness and insomnia to the point of hyperactivity, and the appetite increased four-fold along with rash up and down the injected arm, numbness and tingling in the injected arm, chest discomfort with palpitations, anxiety, headache, stomach pain, malaise, and general limb edema which all persisted until I was able to fall asleep at 6:30am on 3/14. Many of the aforementioned symptoms improved upon wakeup time at 4pm on 3/14, but extreme sleepiness with nausea, dizziness, fatigue, head pain and right eye pain, and palpitations with chest discomfort persisted until 10am on 3/15, during which time only the nausea, dizziness, and fatigue persisted.

Anaphylaxis; Rash all across her leg; Swelling; Itching; Red; Hot; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer concerning a 22-years-old female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced events anaphylaxis, rash all across her leg/rash, swelling, itching,/pruritus, red/erythema, hot/feeling hot. The patient's medical history was not provided. No relevant concomitant medications were reported. On 05 Mar 2021, prior to the onset of the events the patient received first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (lot/batch: 030M20A) Intramuscularly on right leg for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 10 Mar 2021, the patient experienced the event(s) anaphylaxis symptoms of swelling, itching, rash all across her leg. It was red, and hot.S he was a very fragile person with many syndromes and so they took her to the doctor. She was feeling better on 14 Mar 2021. Treatment for the events were none. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported. The outcome of event(s), anaphylaxis, rash all across her leg, swelling, itching, red, hot were reported as recovering on 14 Mar 2021..; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 23-year-old female who experienced a serious expected event of anaphylactic reaction along with unexpected rash, erythema, pruritus, swelling, and feeling hot. Event onset occurred on Day 6 after the first dose of mRNA-1273. Treatment not reported. Events resolving. Based on current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

23 2021-04-10 redness Within 30 seconds of the injection of my second dose of Moderna, I experienced extreme nausea unlike... Read more
Close
Within 30 seconds of the injection of my second dose of Moderna, I experienced extreme nausea unlike any that I have experienced before. Within 1 minute of the injection, my face, arms, chest, and neck flushed and I turned completely red. I felt hot and started to sweat. At the same time, I began having trouble breathing with the sensation that my throat was beginning to close. My eyes filled with tears and I was not able to talk to communicate what was happening. My mom, who was with me at the time of vaccination, asked the administering pharmacist if I could remove my mask because I was having trouble breathing. Throughout this reaction, the pharmacist froze and was visibly in shock of what was happening. Because of this, my mom began asking me questions to figure out what else I was experiencing. Once I was able to remove the mask and breathe deeply, the reaction subsided after two minutes. The pharmacist, after my reaction began to subside, stated that they had an epipen ready to administer if needed. I was never administered the epipen. The pharmacist asked me to wait 30 minutes instead of the general 15 minutes before leaving the site. Because the symptoms went away and did not return within the 30 minutes, I left the site. After the vaccination, I experienced a low-grade fever for 79 hours, chills, a headache, muscle aches, and extreme fatigue. After realizing my reaction was not considered ?normal,? I began to research and realized these symptoms align with anaphylaxis, even though they subsided quickly after experiencing them.

After the first dose (end of March), I had a large red rash at the injection site which lasted almost two weeks. After my second dose (April 20), I had an intense reaction. I was up most of the night freezing cold, leg hair standing on end, and body aching. Had to take a hot shower to cope with the chills. I finally fell asleep for two hours and woke up in hot sweats and an intense headache. I was fine by the afternoon, but developed a new and unusual symptom around 1pm -- sharp localized pains that would intermittently shoot through random parts of my body (mostly legs, but also arms and midsection). They were so bad I would keel over while standing and gasp. Each day since, they have lessened in intensity, but are still somewhat present (it is 11pm on April 26, one week later). Now, I have what I would describe as subtle, localized cramps (?) in random areas (calves, thigh, tricep, back) that come and go -- more of an ache-y sensation but widespread across my body. It is nothing I have experienced before, and only started after the vaccination.

On the morning of 1/8/2021 (exactly 6 days after the first dose of the Moderna vaccine), I woke up with large hives concentrated mostly on my upper body (face, neck, chest, stomach). I tried taking various antihistamines (excluding Benadryl, which would later prove effective) to combat the hives, but they were largely ineffective. The hives shifted throughout the day, starting in my upper body and working their way down to my lower extremities. The next day, exactly one week after receiving the vaccine, I woke up with worse hives (now all over my body, mostly concentrated on my stomach, hips, and legs) and angioedema in my face. Symptoms returned a few hours after discharge, where I continued an oral regimen of the aforementioned medications. The next day, 8 days after the initial dose, my symptoms were equally severe and coupled with gastrointestinal distress, feverishness (likely due to dehydration from the Benadryl) and nausea. This morning (1/11/2021), 9 days after receiving the vaccine, my hives have largely subsisted. In summation, starting 6 days after receiving my first dose of the Moderna vaccine, I experienced 3 full days and nights of severe hives and swelling.

The outcome for the events, passed out twice, pain in the injection site, and slight headache was unknown.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 24 year old female patient, who experienced a serious unexpected event of loss of consciousness and non-serious expected event of injection site pain and headache. On January 21 I received my first dose of Moderna vaccine on my left arm. After the vaccine I had a red lump that was hot and a bruise that only lasted 2 days. Everything was fine until the January 28th when I developed a large red lump during the day while at work that was severely itchy and hot. When I got home from work I had a low grade fever. I made an appointment with my primary care for the next day which was Friday the 29th. My doctor told me she believes I had cellulitis. I was given an antibiotic 2x a day for 7 days. She drew a purple circle around the area and told me that if it goes outside the marked area or I feel any new symptoms, to go to the emergency room. Saturday morning on the 30th i woke up to my entire arm red and hot. I felt like I had a huge sunburn. I couldn?t put my sweatshirt on because it was so hot. The emergency room doctor told me I was fine and to keep taking the antibiotics that were given to me yesterday from my primary care doctor. After the emergency room I went to work and started to feel dizzy and nauseous. My hands became sweaty but the rest of my body was cold. I started having a butterfly feeling in my chest. My Apple Watch alerted me that my heart rate was over 100 bpm. That night before bed I had another low grade fever. On Sunday the 31st I noticed the red area was gone but instead it was a dark purple. I felt okay Sunday besides a rapid pulse. Monday February 1st I woke up out of a dead sleep sweating, butterfly feeling in my chest and dizzy. I tried to take my pulse while laying down but it was so fast I couldn?t keep up with it. I put my Apple Watch on which alerted me immediately that my pulse was 152 bpm. I slowly got up but then I passed out falling off of my bed. I couldn?t get any words out because my heart was beating so fast that I couldn?t breathe. I was sweating horribly and had a hard time walking. Had absolutely no strength in my left hand, my arm was purple/red, cold and numb. My arm felt like someone punched me repeatedly and gave me a dead arm. I called my primary doctors office and they were able to get me in that afternoon. All morning my pulse was spiking and then drastically dropping. About an hour and a half before I went to the doctor everything was fine. I was able to talk but still struggled with breathing while talking. The doctor ordered an EKG which came back clear. My pulse and blood pressure was also fine. The doctor told me she believed all of the symptoms I had were from the medication I take at night (doxazosin-to relax my muscles and help with sleep.) She also told me she believed some of it was my mental health issues taking over. She told me the cellulitis looked fine and sent me home. Later that day I felt exhausted and when I woke up from a nap, I had a fever of 100.5. Took Tylenol and it dropped to 99.5 but wouldn?t go any lower. February 2nd I woke up to a large red ring outside of the purple marker, numb finger tips and butterfly feeling in my chest. All day I received alerts that my pulse was falling and spiking. I sent my primary doctor an email and she told me she didn?t think it was cellulitis anymore, maybe a hematoma but she wasn?t sure. Since January 28th I still struggle everyday with the butterfly feeling in my chest, blurry vision, low grade temps, alerts of pulse, dizziness and breathing difficulties. My arm is always hot, my finger tips are numb and sometimes the strength in my hand is gone. The top of my arm is always a dark purple with red blotches and other times my entire arm is red and hot. When my pulse is very fast, I have a hard time talking, remembering what I was going to say and focusing. I?ve had multiple coworkers ask me if I?m okay because I?ll randomly stop talking and stare off and then I?m alerted that my pulse has either spiked or dropped drastically after spiking. My pulse is never consistent. It is always ranging from 57-155bpm. I realized at first I may have what they call ?COVID arm? but my symptoms haven?t gotten any better. No answers have been given to me or a diagnosis. The first diagnosis that they thought was cellulitis. Then it was ?in my head and behavioral.? Then it was a hematoma. Now it?s an ?I don?t know.? I have tried Benadryl for the itching, ice packs for the days that I?m swollen, Tylenol for the fevers and pain but I never have any relief.

At 17.5 hours (following morning), muscle soreness was present in right arm alone and was mild at rest, moderate with movement. All other symptoms were gone. Experienced fatigue that afternoon (approx. 24 hours post-injection), treated effectively with a short nap and vitamin D (through sun exposure). On the 2nd full day post-injection, right arm muscle soreness is minimal with movement.

VAGINAL ULCER (dose 2 only) I had a 5mm diameter ulcer on the inside of my left labia minora. I was given one week worth of valacyclovir, an antibiotic (which I do not remember the name of), and fluconazole to prevent a (or treat a possible) yeast infection. I took one dose of valacyclovir the evening of the fourth day and the morning of the fifth day with no apparent improvement. I did not take any additional doses, as it was recommended by my provider that if it was not effective within 24 hours, then it may not be effective at all. I took all doses of the antibiotic and fluconazole. I began to see improvements (reduced pain, shrinking size) by the seventh day. The ulcer disappeared completely by the twelfth day.

Initially, there was soreness, swelling, and redness (all around upper arm - a bit below deltoid) around injection site over the course of a few days. The area was warm to the touch compared to the rest of the arm. All symptoms went away after 5 days. Exactly 7 days later, a little bit of the soreness came back and there was a redness marking the size of a 50 cent coin. The next day, the soreness grew and the redness spread and the area became warm to the touch again. I talked to a doctor over video chat to talk about what I should do - I was advised to use an ice compress, which I did a few times on and off. The next day (today), redness spread, but soreness and feeling warm to the touch stayed the same. I went to urgent care and was given 7-day antibiotics and told to use Claritin/Zyrtec to lower my histamines. If anything progresses, I should let the provider know.

The following day, this blotch spread more than an inch down my arm and developed a prominent red ring around the border. For a couple days, I took Zyrtec, thinking I may have been bitten by something, which had no effect. 10 days after getting the vaccine, I had an in-person appointment with my PCP who examined my arm and reported to me that this has been seen in patients who received the Moderna vaccine, usually appearing 5-7 days following vaccine administration. Rapid heartbeat; Shortness of breath; Pain at injection site; Chills; Fatigue; Fever; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer concerning a 25 years-old, female patient who experienced rapid heartbeat/MedDRA PT: tachycardia, shortness of breath/MedDRA PT: dyspnoea, pain at injection site/MedDRA PT: vaccination site pain, chills/MedDRA PT: chills, fatigue/MedDRA PT: fatigue, and fever/MedDRA PT: pyrexia. The patient's medical history included anemia and low immune system. Concomitant product use was not provided by the reporter. On 23 Jan 2021, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot # 025A202A) intramuscularly (injection site not provided) for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 23 Jan 2021, after receiving vaccination, the patient experienced pain at injection site, chills, fever, fatigue and shortness of breath. On 24 Jan 2021, the patient experienced rapid heartbeat. The patient was hospitalized and during hospitalization, heart rate was noted as 125 bpm which reduced down to 110 bpm. The patient was discharged on 25 Jan 2021. Following hospitalization, patient had ongoing fever and was advised to contact hospital for direction regarding readmission. Treatment included self-administered Tylenol, six times daily. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was unknown. The events chills and shortness of breath were considered resolved on 24 Jan 2021. The events pain at injection site, fatigue, and rapid heartbeat were considered resolved on an unknown date. 01/12/21 (First dose on 1/9): Exhaustion/confusion (lasted for about three days), recognized episodes of tachycardia that lasted for weeks; severe pain in right arm at vaccination site that lasted about 2 days. 02/9/21: Received second dose of vaccine on 2/6/21, recognized raised, oblong, red rash not at the location of the vaccination site on the deltoid, but on the top of the upper arm and down near the antecubital fossa that slowly crept down the arm over several days, was gone in about a week; severe arm pain for about 2 days; episodes of racing heart continues, was relieved with rest. 03/15/21-03/26/21: Exhaustion; recognized multiple episodes of tachycardia that was not relieved with rest (around 140 bmp, each episode lasted between 3-6 hours). 03/23/21-03/24/21: Pain in right arm 03/26/21-04/2/21: Recognized exhaustion/confusion, tachycardia that was not relieved with rest. 04/2/21: Right arm swelling and pain. Tachycardia (140 bmp), not relieved with rest. Chest pain/tightness. Arm turned purple and all the vasculature was present in the right arm and chest. Admitted to hospital, ultrasound revealed the subclavian vein was completely occluded down to the basilic vein near the elbow. CT scan showed pulmonary emboli in both lungs. Was placed on heparin drip and released from hospital on 04/4/21. Started on 10 mg Eliquis BID for one week on 4/4, now on 5 mg Eliquis BID for 6 months. 05/19/21: Received diagnosis of Factor V Leiden heterozygous mutation. Arm pain/swelling remains periodically.
